<br>
 Some of the things they seem to be trying now feel like it is just a test to see how it works and if they can implement it in EQ2, if it fails or is good for EQ is no concern for them it seems to me they do not care if it hurts EQ if it helps EQ2 it a win for SOE. That is another thread though. I like the required and recommended levels, some things should not be able to be equipped at level one, fungi tunic, while others scaled as you level like with recommended levels is nice.<br>
<br>
 With RPG's it can be a little different than other games, you dont want some aspects of the game to feel linear and you want the player to feel they can roam and be involved in the world. Of course there needs to be limited factors so a low level character does not wander into a dangerous place without knowing but for the immersion factor it needs to make sense and have a reason other than just saying you are not of sufficent level.<br>
<br>
 Enough of the ramblings, with a little wine it is strange how quick you can get off topic :/. Another suggestion they could try is rather than make some weapons from the past useless or spells they could make things more situational. When Kunark came out, attach a category for the mob type say lizard blood of some type. While old world weapons will work on these new mobs, there effectiveness is not as good as some new Kunark weapons with a bane for lizard or some other value they make them effective for lizardmen. You could make some new spells with a bane similar to GB and DB. To find the new weapons you need to explore, hunt and progress through Kunark. Enter Velious and you have Giants, Dragons and Dorfs blood line so you need to progress through it the same. <br>
<br>
Maybe you need to have required and recommended levels for the weapons or you could add new skills in the expansions that you have to learn in that expansion before you can use the weapons or spells. I think they were on the right track with some bane weapons just how they implemented them was horrid. Not sure if this makes any sense.<br>
<br>
 One of the biggest problems I see wrong with EQ and mudflation now is with new expansions they become useless and while not completly and in every case, they make the past expansion and experiences almost pointless. Sure there is some things to go back to older expansions for, most the time the past expansion seem to die a slow death.<br>
<br>
 I dont think we really need a new backdrop ie new zones with more expansions but some changes to the old ones. CT is one example of a zone many of us grew up with and loved, the revamp breathed new life into it. Before PoP, CT was one of the most popular zones in game even though it was one of the oldest. I was hoping they noticed it but once PoP came out, CT turned into a ghost town again.<br>
<br>
 Sorry for the ramblings hopefully a little of this made some sense. EQ is/has been a great game and I think it could be fun for a long time, do not take some of this as bashing but ways to make EQ better and the game it can be. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pilsainsilverback>Pilsain Silverback</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 876<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/6/03 8:07 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cure for gear mudflation?</span><hr size=1> They need to figure out how to get people to go after appropriate level drops OUTSIDE of the bazaar.  Now, this is my opinion, but that is the D&amp;D model, right?<br>
