Would there be any disadvantages to throwing more training points to players? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nadiar>Nadiar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>Mistyr Smartipants</span><br>  Posts: 1306<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/8/03 4:26 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: hmmm</span><hr size=1> Okay, here is what I would do:<br>
<br>
Step 1: Remove level requirements (recommended is fine though).<br>
<br>
Step 2: Create Quests that allow you to trade No Drop equipment assuming you have the flags from the mob that drops it.<br>
<br>
Step 3: Allow NPC's to return meaningful amounts of cash for items (they could have the servers record data about the bazaar for a few months, and calculate prices based on the lowest 5 servers' average (obviously it would be a fraction of that amount)<br>
<br>
Step 4: Every item should have a tag stating the 'best' current worth of the item if sold to an indifferent NPC with your current charisma.<br>
<br>
Lets look at the following circumstance:<br>
<br>
Stryven won a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Vanazir, Dreamer's Despair</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> but has recently won an upgrade (haha), he goes up to some cool looking White Efreeti mob in potimea, drops it in the trade window, slaps in 100,000 pp, and gets back <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>A model of Vanazir, Dreamer's Despair</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> which is droppable, same stats and classes, but Race: None.<br>
<br>
Stryven runs into the bazaar, slaps it into his Traders satchel for 700,000 pp, then goes to sleep.<br>
<br>
Bindy is looking at the bazaar and notices <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>A model of Vanazir, Dreamer's Despair</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Being too poor, she liquidates her many alts, and then buys it, runs to potimea, hands it into the NPC, and gets his precious Vanazir, Dreamer's Despair in return.<br>
<br>
Sure, it probably means that guilds will end up farming a bit less, but I can guarantee that very shortly pp will be worth quite a bit.<br>
<br>
The PROBLEM with this approach is that it has to be 'intelligent' enough to police the server economies, and adjust the fraction given for items based on how much money is going back into the system.  It also has to note and record when a large number of any specific item is being sold to it, and drop the price accordingly.  But that is how the system always SHOULD have been.  'Cheese' would never have been a problem if the system modified the price of cheese based on the fact that it had purchased 60 billion pp worth of cheese in a single day, and cut the payback in half.  The server should also track &quot;stagnant&quot; money, and assume it has been removed from the money pool.  This eliminates people who quit, and people who have a huge horde of cash, but never buy anything.<br>
<br>
A lot of games talk about a &quot;zero sum&quot; economy, but I believe this is a fallacy.  &quot;Zero sum&quot; just means the rich end-game people who don't spend money get richer, and everyone else becomes more poor.<br>
<br>
Will this fix the economy? I'm not sure.  For one, it might be too late.  Second, it really depends on how many people in the end-game you can get to spend huge sums of money to transfer items they no longer need. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=istari@graffeswizardcompilation>Istari</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br>  Posts: 345<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/9/03 12:15 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> heh</span><hr size=1> It takes a rather lot to get to have a Vanazir. Most guilds consider droppables that are awarded to be guild property- ie BoCs. having all of that farmed to be sold is rather gimpy, not heard of on my server. if I had guild loot that was good, I wouln't sell it in the bazaar personally but rather pass it on- even w/ my own droppables. the raid end of the game really isn't economy, though, given the loot distribution. <br>
<br>
I never really looked into it, but do a lot of guilds let memebrs sell stuff like their awarded BOCs(for lack of a better alternative item)? Even with stuff like emp robe, one hasnt dropped on this server for 4 months and it would be really shitty to see one of our 5 robes wind up in the bazaar. The raid-end of EQ I think really isn't meant for economy since it really isn't individually earned for people's moneybags. Well, I think making a market of raid items is a bit ridiculous myself, just given how all of THAT works. Are you a member of a hardcore raiding guild? They won't be raiding less if they can help it. They all raid on their regular days with perhaps a few scheduled offdays, unless attend is sucking. Raiding isnt a complement to the EQ xp grind for me, it's the main thing keeping me even here.<br>
<br>
The money supply in a mmgorpg is strictly currency too. If I recall right, some 1/4 to 1/3 of a modern money supply is currency. We don't have banking systems, there's no loans, so much of the money supply becomes stagnant. It, too, grows uncontrollably. People print their own cash every time they loot a coin or vendor an item. There's really no problem with that, to consider the money supply you'll want to consider what the money is good for.<br>
<br>
Back WAY long ago I remember the vendor-sucking. People would work on tradeskills and sell stuff to other people and they'd go buy plate, this was before I saw this bronze armor stuff lying around. It was expensive, but the money going in was balanced by the money going out. More importantly, there was a meaning to the exchange of cash- it was actually needed for something and held an exchange value of its own. Old banking systems used to allow you to exchange your money for gold in order to back its currency, which gave much of it value. In EQ now, I find nothing to exchange my fat hoarde of cash for. Currently I buy some very trivial stuff for hero sandwiches and kaladim constitutionals. otherwise I can work on tradeskills(almost baking maxed now). no progress for my character power, however, is even based on cash. I can leave my bank alone and never worry.<br>
<br>
An active economy is neat and all but it's rather difficult to replicate an economy in a virtual world. After all, the study of econonomy is essentially how to allocate scare rescources. We don't have any such thing in a mmgorpg if it's infinite. Back when yaks were worth 10k, people would wait in line to gank SMRs and that like and the stuff could only enter the server as it dropped and there was no alternative for it. Now you can go and AE guk (usually faction) and get 5 yaks an SMR and 2 runed cowls in the time you get your stuff done. All that goes to just one person, and the way it entered the server remains the same. The difference is that lguk used to have 30+ people in there so that the items were divided far more. The prices naturally fell as stuff becomes more common. A more pertinent question perhaps is how this effects the gameplay aspect. Newbies can get a hold of higher end stuff more easily if it's less covetous: do devs want them to have this so much more easily? EQ is more about progressing/fun than about economy- which can be part of the fun itself.<br>
<br>
If raid stuff is sellable like that though I foresee a world of people gearing up, quitting, selling their whole set of armor for player auctions and chumping your guild's work to gear them. Then all of the high end raid loot that shouldn't flood an economy will wind up there, probably to the dislike of the raiding guilds and make the whole concept of raiding totally flipped. Right now I see a couple of people making out with raid stuff to sell on player auctions from another guild, and the other sold stuff unneeded droppables for a peridot fund. it may just be me, but I'd dislike seeing raids turn into just a cash cow action. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nadiar>Nadiar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>Mistyr Smartipants</span><br>  Posts: 1313<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/9/03 2:09 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: heh</span><hr size=1> I was assuming that most of the loot would be transferred to other characters upon leaving.  As far as I know, most members who leave end-game guilds voluntarily leave their droppable guild loot behind.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>An active economy is neat and all but it's rather difficult to replicate an economy in a virtual world. After all, the study of econonomy is essentially how to allocate scare rescources.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Only if you're on a Gold Standard.<br>
<br>
Anyway, this is one of the reasons I personally feel that every server needs an involved Game Master (This is not the same as Customer Service).  <br>
<br>
Anyway, as I said, if you base the payback price essentially on their rarity, you can help circulate money.  That would be the goal of this system, taking money from the high end (those who produce more than they consume) and giving it to the low end (those who consume more than they produce). <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If raid stuff is sellable like that though I foresee a world of people gearing up, quitting, selling their whole set of armor for player auctions and chumping your guild's work to gear them. Then all of the high end raid loot that shouldn't flood an economy will wind up there, probably to the dislike of the raiding guilds and make the whole concept of raiding totally flipped.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Which will happen anyway.  Hence the requirement of Flag restrictions.  By adding the flag restriction, you are making any possible market relatively small.<br>
<br>
In my opinion, playerauctions complete's the economy. If people are willing to pay cash for something, then you have proven the economy is working.<br>
The problem in EQ is this fluctuates madly. One month you will see $1 = 1kpp, the next you will see $3 = 1kpp.  I think it is a pretty good measure of how much the market in EQ is fluctuating.<br>
<br>
(please note that I have never, nor do I believe I ever will buy something from an online auction site for EQ)<br>
<br>
Either way, this is something that is probably too late for EQ, and would have to be investigated heavily before being added to any project.  Many game companies have chosen Player Made items to be the basic item that is purchased. The problem with this is, you have to assume that anything worth doing for money will be done by a large number of people, which means the market is flooded, which means that the item will sell for the very minimum amount, which means that those with the largest supply of money don't need to spend as much....<br>
<br>
EQ2 is going to attempt to make you want to buy trade-skiller stuff, and have items decay so that they fall out of the market on their own. In my opinion, this is a bad idea... It's not going to work like they think it will. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 4683<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/9/03 2:37 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cure for gear mudflation?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The only method I can legitimately think of to fix this is if you *HAD* to pay for some sort of lodging when you were logged off, and taxes.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I would hate this like nothing else..  I already hate how I lose summoned items when I log off--  The game is good enough as it is, I don't need extraneous reasons to stay online when I should be logging off.. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kinanifarslayer>Kinani Farslayer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/9/03 6:49 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cure for gear mudflation?</span><hr size=1> I can get 5% xp much faster than I can get 4k cause I despise plat farming. Scavenging corpse's killed by bored twinks in FP and EC/making my own raw silk etc was fun the first time P. It would not be now with the limied time I have to play. You could most likely get several hundred plat or more with some determined VL farming in any o